Capstone Project¶

Create a Customer Segmentation Report for Arvato Financial Services¶

The task of the project is to analyze demographics data for customers of a German mail-order sales company, comparing the data against demographic information for the general population in Germany. The unsupervised learning techniques to perform customer segmentation will be applied, and the the main features of the core customer group will be described. A data sheet with demographics information for targets of a marketing campaign for the company is also referred; also a supervising model to predict whether individuals are most likely to convert into becoming customers for the company will be utilized.

In this Jupyternote book, the procedure is basically spereated into few parts listed below:

  • Know the data: get to understand the dataset and explore which sections of the datasets need to be wrangled.

  • Data Wrangling: Based on the findings above, apply a function to clean the data, and explain reasons to cope with the features that are uncenessary.

  • Customer Segmentation Report: the method of K-modes is used as an unsupervised learning technnique in the project, and the reason of using this techique is also mentioned. According to the result of clustering, 5 clusters could be formed, and the critical features of the interested cluster are presented.

  • Supervised Learning Model: The true meaning behind the quantitavie values of numerous features is actually representation of each categories. In other words, the major task of this project is to cope with complex features of classification. As a result, sevearl classification algorithms are utilized, and metrics of evaluation is also introduced. Finally, the result of prediction is conveyed.

  • Conclusion: summarize the findings, challenge, and the limitation of my work.

def list_null_percentage (df):
    
    '''
    Description: present null percentage of each column
    
    Input: 
    df : (type:dataframe) the dataframe that would like to present the percentage of null columns
    
    Output:
    list_null_percenrage: A list of columns with null percentage
    '''
    null_percentage_df = ((df.isnull().sum() / df.shape[0]*100).round(2)) 
    null_percentage = null_percentage_df.sort_values(ascending=False).to_string()
    
    return print (null_percentage)
In [89]:
def plot_null_percentage (df, m):
    
    '''
    Description: present null percentage of each column
    
    Input: 
    df : (type:dataframe) the dataframe that would like to present the percentage of null columns
    m : (type: int) number of features with missing values are visualized
    
    Output:
    list_null_percenrage: A list of columns with null percentage
    '''
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    null_percentage_df = (df.isnull().sum() / df.shape[0]*100).round(2)
    plot_null_percentage = null_percentage_df.sort_values(ascending=False)[:m].plot(kind='bar', 
                                                                                     figsize=(20,8), 
                                                                                     fontsize=13, 
                                                                                     color = base_color)
    
    plt.title("Percentage , \nDistribution of null values in the dataset",fontsize=13,fontweight="bold")
    plt.xlabel("Variables",fontsize=13)
    plt.ylabel("Proportion",fontsize=13)
    
    return plot_null_percentage

# lp & wohn is short for LP_* & WOHNLAGE*

def encode_lp_wohn(df):
    """
    Re-encode LP_* & WOHNLAGE columns:
    
    Input: 
    df : (type:dataframe) the dataframe to be transformed
    
    - replace 0s with nan values
    - drop complex and/or duplicate columns
    - split columns with mixed features.
    
    Output:
    df : feature transformed dataframe
    """
    # replace 0s with nan values
    cols = ["LP_LEBENSPHASE_FEIN","LP_LEBENSPHASE_GROB", "LP_FAMILIE_FEIN", "LP_FAMILIE_GROB","WOHNLAGE"]
    df[cols] = df[cols].replace({0: np
                                 .nan})
    
    # drop complex and/or duplicate columns
    df.drop(['LP_FAMILIE_FEIN','LP_STATUS_FEIN','LP_LEBENSPHASE_FEIN','LP_LEBENSPHASE_GROB'], axis=1, inplace=True)
    
    # re-encode LP_STATUS_GROB and LP_FAMILIE_GROB
    status = {1: 1, 2: 1, 3: 2, 
              4: 2, 5: 2, 6: 3, 
              7: 3, 8: 4, 9: 4, 
              10: 5}
    family = {1: 1, 2: 2, 3: 3, 
               4: 3, 5: 3, 6: 4, 
               7: 4, 8: 4, 9: 5, 
               10: 5, 11: 5}
    
    wohn = {1: 1, 2: 1, 3: 2, 
            4: 3, 5: 3, 6: 4, 
            7: 4, 8: 4 }
    
    df["LP_STATUS_GROB"] = df["LP_STATUS_GROB"].map(status)                                              
    df["LP_FAMILIE_GROB"] = df["LP_FAMILIE_GROB"].map(family) 
    df["WOHNLAGE"] = df["WOHNLAGE"].map(wohn)
    
    return df
In [91]:
# pj is short for PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE
def encode_pj(i):
    """
    Re-encode PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE as a binary feature:
    
    0: Mainstream
    1: Avantgarde
    """
    mainstream = [1, 3, 5, 8, 10, 12, 14]
    avantgarde = [2, 4, 6, 7, 9, 11, 13, 15]
    if i in mainstream: 
        return 0
    elif i in avantgarde: 
        return 1
    else:
        return i
In [92]:
# Function to fit the method
def model_training(model, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test):
    '''
    Th function is to customizeof the fit method
    
    Input: 
    model: The model from the list of the classifiers/models
    X_train - The training data
    y_train - The training feature
    X_test - The validation of data
    y_test - The validation of feature
    
    Output: 
    ROC-AUC score 
    Training time
    '''
    t = time.time()
    model = model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_pred = model.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]
    
    roc_score = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred)

    train_time = time.time() - t
    
    return roc_score, train_time
In [93]:
# Function to iterate over classifier and fir method
def test_model(training_models, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test):
    '''
    This function iterates over declared classifiers and calls the custom fit method.
    
    Input: 
    classifiers - The list of the classifiers/models
    X_train - The training data
    y_train - The training features
    X_test - The validation data
    y_test - The validation features
    
    Output: 
    df: (dataframe) The resulting dataframe for comparison
    '''
    result={
    'Training Model':[],
    'ROC Score':[],
    'Training Time':[]
    }
    
    for name, clf in training_models:
        score, t = model_training(clf, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test)
        result['Training Model'].append(name)
        result['ROC Score'].append(score)
        result['Training Time'].append(t)
    
    results_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(result, orient='index').transpose()
    
    return results_df
In [94]:
def evaluate_model_ROC(best_clf, X_test, y_test):
    """Draw ROC curve for the model
    Input:
        Classification Model
        X_test, y_test, Array-like(model_classifer_obj)
    Output: 
        ROC curve
    """
    y_pred = best_clf.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]
    fpr, tpr, th = roc_curve(y_test, y_pred)
    roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr) # compute area under the curve
    plt.figure()
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label='ROC curve (area = %0.2f)' % (roc_auc))
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--')
    plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
    plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.title('Receiver Operating Characteristic Curve')
    plt.legend(loc="lower right")

Further exploration of unknown value¶

In order to avoid values without meaning, we should find out values that map the "Meaning" in the sheet of "DIAS Attributes - Values 2017.csv" belonging to "unknown" or "unknown / no main age detectable". Such values should be treated as "Nan" since we do not know what does it mean.

In [15]:

In [18]:
# Convert values of both datasets (df1&df2) equal to unkown attributes into NaN 

for df in [df1, df2]:
    for column in df.columns:
        if df[column].dtype == np.int64:
            df[column] = df[column].astype(np.float64)
        if column not in set(unknown['Attribute']):
            continue
            
        unknown_value = unknown.loc[unknown['Attribute'] == column].Value.item()
        unknown_value = set(float(x) for x in unknown_value.split(', ')) if type(unknown_value) is str else set([float(unknown_value)])
        df[column] = df[column].mask(df[column].isin(unknown_value), other=np.nan)

  • Compared to Azidas, dataset of Customers have three extra categorical variables, that are 'ONLINE_PURCHASE', 'CUSTOMER_GROUP', and 'PRODUCT_GROUP'.

  • 'CAMEO_DEUG_2015' & 'CAMEO_INTL_2015':

    • Convert "X" or "XX" as "Nan"

  • 'CAMEO_INTL_2015' can be split into two seperated features:

'CAMEO_INTL_2015_WEALTH' (Based on the first value of the origian value): 

* 1. Wealthy <br>
* 2. Prosperous <br>
* 3. Comfortable <br>
* 4. Less Affluent <br>
* 5. Poor <br>

"CAMEO_INTL_2015_STATUS" (Based on the 2nd value of the origin value): 

* 1. Pre-Family Couples & Singles<br>
* 2. Young Couples With Children<br>
* 3. Families With School Age Children<br>
* 4. Older Families &  Mature Couples<br>
* 5. Elders In Retirement
  • For feature 'OST_WEST_KZ':
    • Converted to 0/1 with 0 = OST and 1 = WEST
  • 'CAMEO_DEU_2015' and'D19_LETZTER_KAUF_BRANCHE',''EINGEFUEGT_AM' have too many unique values, and plan to drop them.
  • 'LNR' looks like an unique identifier --> will drop.

  • "0" should be treated as NaN since it is not discribed in "DIAS ATTRIBUTES - Values 2017"
  • "LP_LEBENSPHASE_FEIN" and "LP_LEBENSPHASE_GROB" should be removed since they have complex unique features.
  • The discription in "DIAS ATTRIBUTES - Values 2017" reveals that feature names end with "FEIN" have detail information with those end with "GROB", and these pair features actualy address identical information. As a result, we should drop "LP_STATUS_FEIN" and "LP_FAMILIE_FEIN", and reserve "LP_STATUS_GROB" and "LP_FAMILIE_GROB"

  • "LP_STATUS_GROB" and "LP_FAMILIE_GROB" can be re-encoded as below:

    • "LP_STATUS_GROB"
      1: low-income
      2: average-income
      3: independant
      4: houseowner
      5: top earner
    • LP_FAMILIE_GROB
      1: single
      2: couple
      3: single parent
      4: family
      5: multi-person household

  • According to the "DIAS ATTRIBUTES - Values 2017", further feature engineering can be:

    • "PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE" can be encoded into binaray (mainstream & avantgarde) from numeric values ranging from 1 to 15
    • "WOHNLAGE"
      1: Good Neighbourhood
      2: Average
      3: Poor Neighbourhood
      4: Rural

  • The plots above demonstrate the percentage of missing values for both datasets. For Azdias (df1), clearly most of the columns are less than 20% of missing values; thus 20% is selected as a threshold to remove features with too many missing values.
  • As for the rows with missing values, I would remove them since it does not make sense to impute with other values since most of the numeric values contain with a categorical meaning.
  • No duplicates rows are found.

Summary of Data Wranggling¶

In 'CAMEO_DEUG_2015' & 'CAMEO_INTL_2015':

  • Convert "X" or "XX" as "Nan"

'CAMEO_INTL_2015' can be split into two seperated features:

"CAMEO_INTL_2015_WEALTH" (Based on the first digit of the origian value): 

* 1: Wealthy <br>
* 2: Prosperous <br>
* 3: Comfortable <br>
* 4: Less Affluent <br>
* 5: Poor <br>

"CAMEO_INTL_2015_STATUS" (Based on the 2nd digit of the origin value): 

* 1: Pre-Family Couples & Singles<br>
* 2: Young Couples With Children<br>
* 3: Families With School Age Children<br>
* 4: Older Families &  Mature Couples<br>
* 5: Elders In Retirement

For feature 'OST_WEST_KZ':

  • Convert: 0 = OST and 1 = WEST
  • Convert dtype as float

Columns to be removed:

  • 'CAMEO_DEU_2015','D19_LETZTER_KAUF_BRANCHE', 'LNR' , 'EINGEFUEGT_AM'
  • "LP_LEBENSPHASE_FEIN", "LP_LEBENSPHASE_GROB", "LP_STATUS_FEIN" and "LP_FAMILIE_FEIN"
  • Columns with more than 20% of missing values

**Remove rows with missing value

Feature Engineering:

  • "LP_STATUS_GROB" and "LP_FAMILIE_GROB" can be re-encoded as below:
    • "LP_STATUS_GROB"
      1: low-income
      2: average-income
      3: independant
      4: houseowner
      5: top earner
    • "LP_FAMILIE_GROB"
      1: single
      2: couple
      3: single parent
      4: family
      5: multi-person household
    • "PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE" can be encoded into binaray (mainstream & avantgarde) from numeric values ranging from 1 to 15
    • "WOHNLAGE"
      1: Good Neighbourhood
      2: Average
      3: Poor Neighbourhood
      4: Rural

Clean the dataframe¶

In [38]:
def clean_dataframe(df):
    
    # Drop columns above threshold (20%)
    df.drop(columns=col_to_drop, axis=1, inplace=True)
    
    # Drop rows above threshold (10%)
#    per_missing_row = df.isnull().mean(axis=1) * 100
#    df = df[per_missing_row <= n]
#    df.dropna(axis=0, inplace=True)
   
    # Convert 'X' and 'XX' as nan
    col = ["CAMEO_DEUG_2015", "CAMEO_INTL_2015"]
    df[col] = df[col].replace({"X": np.nan, "XX": np.nan})
    df[col] = df[col].astype(float)

    # re-encode binary categorical variables
    df['OST_WEST_KZ'].replace(['O','W'], [0, 1], inplace=True)
    df['OST_WEST_KZ'] = df['OST_WEST_KZ'].astype(float)

    
    # Remove uncecessary features
    df.drop(['CAMEO_DEU_2015', 'EINGEFUEGT_AM','LNR'], axis=1, inplace=True)
      
    # re-encode CAMEO_INTL_2015
    df['CAMEO_INTL_2015_WEALTH'] = df['CAMEO_INTL_2015'].apply(lambda x: np.floor(pd.to_numeric(x)/10))
    df['CAMEO_INTL_2015_STATUS'] = df['CAMEO_INTL_2015'].apply(lambda x: pd.to_numeric(x)%10)
    df.drop('CAMEO_INTL_2015', axis=1, inplace=True)
    
    # re-encode LP-related features and Wohn
    df = encode_lp_wohn(df)
    
    # Re-encode PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE
    df['PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE'] = df['PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE'].apply(lambda x: encode_pj(x))
    
    # Remove features if they are available
    try:
        df.drop(['PRODUCT_GROUP','CUSTOMER_GROUP','ONLINE_PURCHASE'], axis=1,inplace=True)
    except:
        pass
    
    # Drop rows with missing value
    df.dropna(axis=0, inplace=True)
        
     
    return df

df1_clean = clean_dataframe(df1) 
df2_clean = clean_dataframe(df2)

Further removal of features with numeric values¶

For features with discrete values, correlation among variables is not necessarily to be checked since each discrete numeric digit represents a type of category. As a result, such features should be treated as categorical variables without onehot encoding.

In addition, features with continuous values should be reviewed. It would be too complex and time consuming to run algorithm mixing with too many continuous values and features with discrete values (encoded categorical variables).

Thus, I am going to find continuous value features by visual review and by mapping "meaning" based on numeric value. After the dataset is transformed based on below categoris, features with coninuous values shall be removed.

In [41]:

Customer Segmentation Report¶

After the procedure above, only variables with encoded categorical features and binary features are reserved.
Features with continuous values are removed since there are only 10 variables and would have limited impact for the modeling. Compared to the method of K-means whcih calculates Euclidean distance, K-modes replaces it with dissimilarity metric by using mode rathan than mean or median to represent the clusters. As a result, the method of K-modes is more appropriate to cope with cateforical datasets for further analysis.

Meanwhile, PCA (Principle Component Analysis) is not a proper tool for the datasets. Even though all the categorical and binary features are encoded with numeric values, PCA won’t be effective with encoded categorical variables due to lack of mathematical meaning for variance structure. It does not make sense to break down the variance for the numeric encoded values.

  • Note: Since the datasets are too large and the limitation of calculation power of my personal laptop, it's time consuming for modeling and thus datasets are randomly selected 5K accordingly.

Approach 1 -- K-modes based on "Cao"¶

In [51]:
# Choose the optimal K -- By "Cao"

cost = []
centroids = [2,5,10,12,15]

for cluster in centroids:
    kmode = KModes(n_clusters=cluster, init = 'Cao', n_init = 1, 
                   verbose=1, max_iter=3,random_state = 42)
    kmode.fit_predict(df1_matrix)
    cost.append(kmode.cost_)

# Convert the results into a dataframe
print(pd.DataFrame(sorted(zip(centroids, cost), key=lambda x: x[1]), columns=['Centroids','Cost']))

# Plot
plt.plot(centroids,cost, linestyle='-', linewidth=3, marker='o')
plt.title('Elbow Method For Optimal k -- Based on "Cao"')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters', fontsize = 12)
plt.ylabel('Cost', fontsize = 12)
plt.show();

# Choose the optimal K -- By "Huang"

cost = []

                   verbose=1, max_iter=3, random_state = 42)
    kmode.fit_predict(df1_matrix)
    cost.append(kmode.cost_)

# Convert the results into a dataframe

plt.title('Elbow Method For Optimal k -- Based on "Huang"')

Evaluation¶

  • The Elbow method is applied to determine the optimal number of clusters. Two approches with "Cao" and "Huang" are used to evalute which algorithm would lead to a more reasonable result.
  • Both methods suggest similar results that I would take "5" as the optimal number of K to proceed

Interpretation of K-modes Clustering (k=5)¶

Fit k-modes into df1 (Azdias)¶

In [53]:
# Convert dataframes to matrix
df1Matrix = df1_clean.to_numpy()
df2Matrix = df2_clean.to_numpy()
In [54]:
kmodes = KModes(n_clusters = 5, init = 'Huang',n_init = 1, 
                verbose=1, max_iter=3, random_state = 42)
    
# Fit the model
y_pred_df1 = kmodes.fit_predict(df1Matrix) 
    
# Create "cluster_id" column in the dataframe
df1_clean['cluster_id']= kmodes.labels_
df1_sort_cluster_id = df1_clean.cluster_id.value_counts().sort_index()

  • Clearly, cluster 3 and 4 show a strong representation of the customers compared to the population.
  • Meanwhile, clusters 0,1,2 are the ones with less power of representativity to the customers.
  • Based on the process above, the demographic features for the centroids of each cluster are presented. That is, the characteristics of potential clients can be determined when the features of cluster 3 and 4 are examined. On the contrary, for those who may not be the customers could be justified when cluster 0, 1 and 2 are reviewed.
  • For example, the interested cluster would be:
    1. Middle class who are consumption-oriented
    2. distance to the next urban center is 50-60km
    • Note: "AKT_DAT_KL", "ANZ_KINDER", and "ARBEIT" are not described in the sheet of "DIAS Attributes -- Values 2017".

Data wranggling for the training dataset¶

In [69]:
# Convert missing and unknown values to nan values
# attributes_values = attributes_values[attributes_values.columns[1:]]  

attributes_values = attributes_values[attributes_values['Attribute'].notnull()]
unknown = attributes_values[attributes_values['Meaning'].isin(['unknown', 'unknown / no main age detectable'])]

for col in df_train.columns:
    if df_train[col].dtype == np.int64:
        df_train[col] = df_train[col].astype(np.float64)
    if col not in set(unknown['Attribute']):
        continue
        
    unknown_value = unknown.loc[unknown['Attribute'] == col].Value.item()
    unknown_value = set(float(x) for x in unknown_value.split(', ')) if type(unknown_value) is str else set([float(unknown_value)])
    df_train[col] = df_train[col].mask(df_train[col].isin(unknown_value), other=np.nan)

def clean_supervised_dataframe(df, attributes_values, col_to_drop_train):
    
    # Drop columns above threshold (20%)
#    df.drop(columns=col_to_drop_train, axis=1, inplace=True)
    
    # Drop numeric cols
    df.drop(columns=numeric_cols, axis=1, inplace=True)
   
    # Convert 'X' and 'XX' as nan
    col = ["CAMEO_DEUG_2015", "CAMEO_INTL_2015"]
    df[col] = df[col].replace({"X": np.nan, "XX": np.nan})
    df[col] = df[col].astype(float)

    # re-encode binary categorical variables
    df['OST_WEST_KZ'].replace(['O','W'], [0, 1], inplace=True)
    df['OST_WEST_KZ'] = df['OST_WEST_KZ'].astype(float)

    
    # Remove uncecessary features
    ##"ALTER_HH", "ALTERSKATEGORIE_FEIN" are removed based on visual check (due to too many unique values)
    df.drop(['CAMEO_DEU_2015', 'EINGEFUEGT_AM',
             'D19_LETZTER_KAUF_BRANCHE',"ALTERSKATEGORIE_FEIN"], axis=1, inplace=True)
      
    # re-encode CAMEO_INTL_2015
    df['CAMEO_INTL_2015_WEALTH'] = df['CAMEO_INTL_2015'].apply(lambda x: np.floor(pd.to_numeric(x)/10))
    df['CAMEO_INTL_2015_STATUS'] = df['CAMEO_INTL_2015'].apply(lambda x: pd.to_numeric(x)%10)
    df.drop('CAMEO_INTL_2015', axis=1, inplace=True)
    
    # re-encode LP-related features and Wohn
    df = encode_lp_wohn(df)
    
    # Re-encode PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE
    df['PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE'] = df['PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE'].apply(lambda x: encode_pj(x))
    
    # Remove features if they are available
    try:
        df.drop(['PRODUCT_GROUP','CUSTOMER_GROUP','ONLINE_PURCHASE'], axis=1,inplace=True)
    except:
        pass

    # Convert features dtype==int64 to float
    col_int = df.columns[df.dtypes.eq('int64')]
    df[col_int] = df[col_int].astype(float)
    
    # Drop columns above threshold (20%)
    df.drop(columns=col_to_drop_train, axis=1, inplace=True)
    
    # Drop rows with missing values
    df.dropna(axis=0, inplace=True)
     
    return df

df_train = clean_supervised_dataframe(df_train, attributes_values, col_to_drop_train)

Model Training¶

The dataset shows a problem of classification. Thus, few classifiers are used in later modeling for the prediction of whether an individual becomes a customer of the campaign.

Metrics of evaluation
The evaluation metric for this interested task is AUC for the ROC curve, relative to the detection of customers from the mail campaign.

A receiver operating characteristic (ROC) curve is a graphic plot used to demonstrate the true positive rate (TPR, also known as recall, which is the proportion of correctly labeled actual customers) against the false positive rate (FPR, proportion of non-customers labeled as customers).

Mathematical formulas of TPR and FPR are defined as:

TPR = TP / (TP + FN)
FPR = FP /(FP + TN)

where

TP = ture positive

FP = false postive

TN = true negative

FN = false negative

Improvement of the seleceted algorithms
The ROC score of each algorithm and the time of training are considered as major criteria whether the model would be applied. The tenique of GriedSearch will be applied fo find out the best combination of parameters. Such hyper-tuning would further improve the performance of the models.

# Randomly take 80% of original data as sample
df_train = df_train.sample(frac=0.8)
In [78]:
X = df_train.iloc[:, df_train.columns != 'RESPONSE']
y = df_train['RESPONSE']
In [80]:
# Scale the data
scaler= StandardScaler()
X_train = scaler.fit_transform(X)
In [81]:
# Split the dataset into Train and Test set
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.20, random_state=42)
In [82]:
# Classifiers to check the performance
Classifiers = [("Logistic Regression", LogisticRegression(random_state=42)),
         ("Decision Tree", DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42)),
         ("Random Forest", RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)),
         ("Gradient Boosting", GradientBoostingClassifier(random_state=42)),
         ("AdaBoost", AdaBoostClassifier(random_state=42))]
In [83]:
# Funciton application
test_model(Classifiers, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test)
Out[83]:
Training Model ROC Score Training Time
0 Logistic Regression 0.66174 0.490284
1 Decision Tree 0.506458 0.722162
2 Random Forest 0.578227 3.23643
3 Gradient Boosting 0.759561 18.53092
4 AdaBoost 0.731138 4.268291

The table above demonstrates the ROC score of each classifier. Compared to the benchmark model (Logistic Regression), the GradientBoostingClassifier shows the highest score, while it also takes the most time for training. The AdaBoost reveals the 2nd best score and takes less time to train. As a result, I would choose these two classifiers (GradientBoosting & AdaBoost) for hyper parameter tuning.

Hyper Tuning -- Grid Search¶

GradientBoost Classifier¶

In [84]:
# Grid serach for GradientBoostClassifier model
# I've choose the paramters after browes this article. 
# https://www.analyticsvidhya.com/blog/2016/02/complete-guide-parameter-tuning-gradient-boosting-gbm-python/
# The values of the parameter are basically used by try & error

gbc = GradientBoostingClassifier(random_state=42)

parameters_gbc = {'subsample': [0.8], 
              'n_estimators': [100],
              'max_depth': [8], 
              'min_samples_split': [2, 4],
              'learning_rate': [0.1, 0.2]
             }
In [85]:
# Fit the grid search object to the training data and find the optimal parameters
gbc_grid = GridSearchCV(gbc, parameters_gbc, scoring = 'roc_auc', verbose=2, cv=2)

gbc_grid.fit(X_train, y_train)

Conclusion¶

Coping with the data was certainly among the biggest challenges in this project. However, it's very interesting to engage in the exercies comply with the problems of real world. Dealing with the huge number of missing values and many different types of features could make a gigantic difference on final performance of the model. Customers and general population are clustered into 5 groups, based on the elbow methods of K-modes. The specific characteristics of these two interested focus groups can be broadly identified as middle class who are consumption-oriented and for those live in the distance to the next urban center for 50-60km, while there are still few variables are not explained in the provided document.
.

To estimate the feedback of customers, the Gradient Boosting Classifier is proved to be the better performed model although it also takes the most of the time for prediction. I believe that there is still room for improvement. Specifically, the following changes to my approach could be considered to optimize achievement in the project:

  • A better method to deal with highly imbalanced target
  • Verify different approaches to standardize and scale features. For example, Min-Max-Scaler can be utilized rather than Standard Scaler
  • Due to the limitation of my calculator, I have to randomly extract fewer sample from the dataset. The result of elbow methods of K-modes would be different if all samples are applied. Similarly, In order to avoid spending too much time on training, only 80% of samples in supervised learning are selected, which may also lead to the differnt outcome.
  • Not all parameters are adopt in hyper-tuning.

The result of the project is far from perfect; nevertheless, I hope the process and result presented can be a good practice for further application in the real world.
